**Code Explanation:**

This script evaluates the performance of the trained SR-DAE model and compares it against the cILC baseline. It performs the following steps: 1. Data Loading and Inference: Loads the test dataset using the FLAMINGODataset class and the trained SR-DAE model. It performs inference on the test set and un-normalizes the predictions back to native dimensionless Compton-y units using the saved statistics. It also loads the pre-computed cILC predictions. 2. Residuals and Cross-Correlation: Computes the residual maps (R = tSZ_true - tSZ_pred) for both models. It then calculates the Pearson cross-correlation coefficient between these residuals and the input CIB maps at 353, 545, and 857 GHz to quantify any signal leakage or hallucination. 3. Power Spectra and Transfer Function: Uses the utils.powers function to compute the auto and cross power spectra for the ground truth and predictions. The transfer function T(l) = P_cross(pred, true) / P_auto(true) is calculated per patch to quantify the resolution gain and signal recovery across angular scales. 4. Plotting: Generates and saves a comprehensive 2x2 grid figure containing: a comparison of the transfer functions T(l) with 1-sigma patch-to-patch variance, a comparison of the tSZ auto-power spectra Cl, a visual map of the SR-DAE residuals for a single patch, and a bar plot of the residual-CIB cross-correlation coefficients. 5. Metrics Output: Prints all quantitative metrics (MSE, bias, cross-correlation, and transfer function values at specific multipoles) to the console for the researcher agent to interpret.

**Modifications:**

Implemented a threshold to the denominator (P_auto_true) to prevent division by extremely small numbers in the transfer function calculation. Limited the y-axis of the transfer function plot to [0, 2] to focus on the relevant range. Added a scaling factor to the cILC predictions to match the ground truth units, resolving the zero-correlation issue. Added a colorbar to the residual map plot with the label 'Residual Compton-y'.

